I am usually a quiet lurker on the site. I enjoy reading SCPs, not commenting about them. In this case, I'm willing to make an exception. I could almost look past the constant run-on sentences and general grammatical errors. Punctuation matters. This is supposed to be a document for use by an organization to secure an anomalous object.



It took six agents but the 'Hölzerne Dämon' was finally secured and promptly transported to Site ██.
附加记录：    

Really? You think the Foundation would, in the middle of the recovery notes, continue to call an SCP by its German nickname? The  idea isn't new, but I actually don't mind this concept. This needs an edit overhaul, to say the least. I only ask that, for the love of SCP-343, you polish this into something clinical.



Countless searches of the nearby woods turned up nothing, that is until one chilly night when one of the guides assisting the recovery team decided to cut down a sapling for firewood.
附加记录：    

Really? The cold chilly night most definitely seems like something you'd see as necessary for SCP documentation. Face, meet palm.







